holdings.text: In order to be entitled to be enrolled as an elector of a Municipality under s. 30 sub-s. (2), a person has to fulfill two conditions: (1) entitled under Representation of the People Act, 1950 to be registered in Parliamentary electoral roll if constituency co-extensive with Municipality, and (2) name registered in Parliamentary electoral roll comprising the Municipality.

anchor.surface_text: It is clear from s. 30, sub-s.  2 , of the Regulation that in order to be entitled to be enrolled as an elector of a Municipality, a person has to fulfill two companyditions, viz.,  1  that he should be entitled under the Re. presentation of the People Act, 1950  XLIII of 1950  to be registered in the electoral roll for a Parliamentary Constituency if that Constituency had been companyextensive with the Municipality nd  2  that his name should be registered in the electoral roll for a Parliamentary Constituency companyprising the Municipality.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Textual interpretation of s.30(2) requires both entitlement to registration and actual registration; first condition subject to scrutiny.

holdings.text: Fulfilment of first condition under s.30(2) subject to scrutiny; revision of rolls, adjudication of claims and objections required under s.43(c) for proper electoral rolls.

anchor.surface_text: In order, therefore, to determine whether a person is entitled to be enrolled as an elector of a Municipality, it would be necessary to ascertain in the first instance whether he is entitled to be registered in the electoral roll for the Parliamentary Constituency. ... The fulfillment of the first companydition, however, would be subject to scrutiny and it would be open to any resident of the Municipality to object to the enrolment of a particular person as an elector of the Municipality.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Purposive reading with s.43(c); natural justice demands opportunity for objections and revision to ensure qualifications.
